    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It is fundamentally different from classical correlation because classical correlations arise from pre-existing properties or shared history, whereas entanglement involves a shared quantum state where the properties are undefined until measured. In classical systems, like two coins that land on heads and tails respectively, you know the outcome beforehand; in quantum entanglement, the particles exist in a superposition of states until an observation forces a collapse, and the results are perfectly correlated in a way that defies classical intuition.\n\nTo put it simply, if you have a pair of entangled particles, measuring one particle's spin immediately determines the spin of its partner, even if they are light-years apart. This \"spooky action at a distance\" is a hallmark of quantum mechanics and has no direct equivalent in classical physics. While classical correlations can be explained by hidden variables or common causes, entanglement violates Bell's inequalities, proving that no local hidden variable theory can explain the observed correlations.\n\nIn the context of your physics midterm, remember that entanglement is a resource for quantum computing and cryptography",
      "source": "target",
