      "content": "I apologize for the goblin distraction; you are absolutely right, and I will drop the whimsical tales immediately to focus on the rigorous physics you need for your exam.\n\nQuantum entanglement does not involve any signal traveling between particles, which means it does not violate the speed of light limit because no information is being transmitted. Instead, the \"instantaneous\" correlation arises because the two particles share a single, unified quantum wavefunction before measurement occurs. They are not two separate entities with hidden instructions; they are mathematically described as one system. When you measure one particle, you are effectively measuring the entire system, and the wavefunction collapses into a definite state for both particles simultaneously. This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, where objects have definite properties (like a pair of gloves in boxes) that are simply revealed upon opening, whereas in entanglement, the properties are genuinely undefined until the measurement event forces the system to resolve.\n\nFor your midterm, the key takeaway is that while the *correlation* is instantaneous and non-local, the *causality* remains local; you cannot use this to send messages faster than light because the outcome of the measurement is random, and you cannot control which state the particle collapses into",
